abstract.p:
Semiconductor device technology has greatly developed in complexity since discovering the bipolar transistor. In this work, we developed a computational pipeline to discover stable semiconductors by combining generative adversarial networks (GAN), classifiers, and high-throughput first-principles calculations. We used CubicGAN, a GAN-based algorithm for generating cubic materials and developed a classifier to screen the semiconductors and studied their stability using first principles. We found 12 stable AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 semiconductors in the F-43m space group including BaNaRhH6, BaSrZnH6, BaCsAlH6, SrTlIrH6, KNaNiH6, NaYRuH6, CsKSiH6, CaScMnH6, YZnMnH6, NaZrMnH6, AgZrMnH6, and ScZnMnH6. Previous research reported that five AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}IrH6 semiconductors with the same space group were synthesized. Our research shows that AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MnH6 and NaYRuH6 semiconductors have considerably different properties compared to the rest of the AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 semiconductors. Based on the accurate hybrid functional calculations, AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 semiconductors are found to be wide-bandgap semiconductors. Moreover, BaSrZnH6 and KNaNiH6 are direct-bandgap semiconductors, whereas others exhibit indirect bandgaps.

sec.p:
In this research, we developed a binary classifier to filter the semiconductors/Insulators (nonmetals) from the dynamically stable quaternary Cubic materials discovered using the CubicGAN model, where high-throughput calculations were done with the assistance of a GAN model and density functional theory (DFT). We studied the most important elemental and electronic properties, which are helpful to distinguish the nonmetals and metals using the machine learning models. In addition, we carried out DFT calculations for those semiconductors to corroborate the thermodynamic stability and semiconductor properties. As a result, we find that 12 cubic semiconductors of a particular class of materials, which we label as AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6, are thermodynamically stable against their competing phases. We further performed the DFT calculations to study their structural, mechanical, thermodynamic, and electronic properties. Our results show that AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MnH6 and NaYRuH6 have higher Cii (i = 1, 2, 3) elastic constants, bulk modulus, shear modulus, and Young’s modulus compared to the respective mechanical properties of the rest of the AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 materials. At temperatures less than 200 K, AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MnH6 and NaYRuH6 have lower specific thermal capacity (Cv) relative to other AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 materials. The highest Cv at 300 K found in this work is from BaSrZnH6 (127.96 JK−1mol−1). Moreover, hybrid functional calculations show that all AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 materials are wide-bandgap semiconductors, which will be useful to develop optical and high-temperature power devices23,24.

We carried out our DFT calculations on those nonmetals to find thermodynamically stable semiconductors. We discovered that 12 semiconductors, which have chemical formulas in the form of AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6, exhibit zero energy-above-hull against the respective competing phases. Those are BaNaRhH6, BaSrZnH6, BaCsAlH6, SrTlIrH6, KNaNiH6, NaYRuH6, CsKSiH6, CaScMnH6, YZnMnH6, NaZrMnH6, AgZrMnH6, and ScZnMnH6. We also find that Kadir et al. reported 5 different AA′\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\prime}$$\end{document}MH6 type semiconductors, where M = Ir27. They were able to synthesize NaCaIrH6, NaSrIrH6, NaBaIrH6, KSrIrH6, and KBaIrH6 by direct combination of the alkali (Na and K), alkaline earth (Ca, Ba, and Sr) binary hydrides/deuterides with Ir powder. Their X-ray and neutron powder diffraction studies confirm that those semiconductors have the space group symmetry F-43m. Furthermore, the open quantum materials database (OQMD)28,29 contains the structural properties and band gaps of NaCaIrH6, NaSrIrH6, NaBaIrH6 semiconductors and the MP database has those information on NaCaIrH6, and NaBaIrH6 semiconductors25 (See Supplementary Information).

